A chemical plant explosion in China's northeast caused a pollution crisis in the Songhua River, affecting millions in Harbin.
The Jilin Petroleum and Chemical Company is blamed for the disaster, prompting shutdowns of water supplies.
The government allocated funds for cleanup efforts, while experts worked to dilute pollutants.
China informed Russia of the situation, pledging cooperation.
Measures were taken to safeguard water quality and public health.
Despite concerns, experts believe the pollution will not severely impact rural areas.
Efforts to mitigate the crisis include increased water discharge and monitoring.
The government vows to crack down on polluting industries and prioritize environmental protection for the future.
